source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-1507
Reason: The target compound contains multiple functional groups which influence its melting point: a quinoxaline core, which is a heterocyclic aromatic compound with nitrogen atoms, and keto groups attached to tertiary butyl groups. The quinoxaline core has a relatively high melting point due to its planar and rigid structure, as well as strong π-π stacking interactions between molecules. This core structure is similar to quinoxaline, which has a melting point of around 30-35 degrees. Adding to this, the keto groups can engage in dipole-dipole interactions, providing an additional increase in the melting point. The tertiary butyl groups, being bulky, will also affect the melting point due to increased molecular weight and van der Waals interactions, but their branching may disrupt the crystal packing, potentially reducing the melting point compared to a linear alkyl chain. Estimating the contributions of each functional group: quinoxaline core: +30 (basic aromatic nitrogen-containing heterocycle); keto groups: +40 each (dipole-dipole interactions and contribute to the rigidity of the molecule); tertiary butyl groups: +10 each (increase in van der Waals interactions; steric hindrance may slightly reduce the effect). The compound has two keto groups and two tertiary butyl groups. So, the total prediction would be 30 + 2*(40) + 2*(10) = 130.
